Lose a few header checks on Haiku. [skip ci]

Haiku has <net/if.h> and <net/if_dl.h> and <net/if_types.h>, and
pcap-haiku.c uses neither HAVE_NET_IF_H nor HAVE_NET_IF_DL_H nor
HAVE_NET_IF_TYPES_H, so the checks have no purpose.  This works as
expected on Haiku hrev57672.

README.windows.md: pick up some improvements from the tcpdump file. [skip ci]

The tcpdump file has formatting improvements and fixes to the
command-line section, and also has a stub MinGW section.

When necessary, trust the OS to implement ffs().

Eliminate some dead code and two more build-time checks in Autoconf and
CMake.

Include <config.h> unconditionally

Builds using Autotools or CMake generate config.h, thus remove the
'#ifdef HAVE_CONFIG_H'/'#endif'.

Remove also the 'add_definitions(-DHAVE_CONFIG_H)' in CMakeLists.txt.

CMake: remove some unchecked-for HAVE_ values.

Those were copied and pasted from config.h.in, which defined them
because autoconf inserts tests for them in all generated scripts, even
if nobody needs the test.

We don't test for them, so we might as well just leave them out of
cmakeconfig.h.in.

While we're at it, change a comment to match config.h.in, and fix the
capitalization of Npcap in a comment.

Autoconf: Use AC_DEFINE() more consistently. [skip appveyor]

Where a comment says "Define to 1 if...", actually define the macro
to 1 -- this way the resulting config.h looks less ambiguous.

CMake: Lose HAVE_STRINGS_H as well.

It is neither defined nor used.

Include <config.h> rather than "config.h"

See the 69fcdc66ba2b352ea1c79277d3815e55f7c8ab34 commit message for
for the rationale.
Autoconf: Lose AC_C_INLINE: inline is in C99. [skip appveyor]

CMake: Remove unnecessary header checks.

The checks for <inttypes.h> and <stdint.h> always succeed in a C99
environment, thus HAVE_INTTYPES_H and HAVE_STDINT_H are always defined,
but that is irrelevant because the code includes the headers regardless
of the macros.  Likewise, the check for <bitypes.h> always fails because
the header is supposed to be <sys/bitypes.h>, but that is irrelevant
because CMake does not use the test result and the code does not use the
header since commit a8f73cd.

While at it, lose the no-op HAVE_STDLIB_H and HAVE_STRING_H too.

rpcapd: update a comment.

The -S flag causes TLS to be used over *all* TCP sockets, not just the
data socket, so the user's password is, at least, encrypted by TLS.
(There's no DTLS support for a UDP data socket.)

pcap(3PCAP): Refer to BPF instead of PF. [skip ci]

pfconfig(8) is specific to PF in Ultrix and Tru64 Unix.

List more contributors in CREDITS. [skip ci]

This represents all commits to the master branch since libpcap-1.10-bp.

Note that dates *before* the Epoch aren't supported in pcap. [skip ci]

Making the time stamp unsigned means we don't support dates prior to
1970-01-01 00:00:00 UTC.

The time stamp in pcap packet headers has two unsigned 32-bit values.

When writing a pcap packet record, cast the seconds and microseconds
values to bpf_u_int32, as that's the type of the values in the record
header.  Update the sell-by date of pcap files; making them unsigned
means pcap files don't have a Y2.038K problem, but it does have a
Y2.106K problem.
CHANGES: another change in main and 1.10. [skip ci]

usb-linux: reorganize the isochronous length handling code.

Put useful inline functions, used both by the capture code and the
savefile length fixup code, into pcap-usb-linux-common.h; some of those
came from, or are based on routines in, pcap-usb-linux-common.c, which
we remove.

When capturing, all we need to do is check whether a message with data
is a "this is complete" incoming isochronous transfer event and, if so,
use the routine to calculate its original length.

Pull the routine to fix up the original length into
pcapint_post_process().

When reading savefiles, we need to do additional checks to guess whether
the length needs fixing and to determine whether the number of
descriptors is sane and whether we have all the descriptors; do that in
pcapint_post_process().

Add some additional checks.

Call the "len" field of pcap's metadata header the "original length"
rather than the "on-the-wire" length; that matches the terminology from
the current versions of the pcap and pcapng specs, and doesn't imply
that the length is the length of the packet on the transmission medium,
as that's not always the case - for USB, it's computed based on
information from the endpoint on which we're capturing, and may also
include padding between isochronous data chunks.
CHANGES: autogen.sh etc. is in 1.10.x as well. [skip ci]
CHANGES: add a change backported to 1.10. [skip ci]

usb-linux: do a sanity check on the number of descriptors.

The Linux binary USB monitor code limits the number of isochronous
descriptors to 128; if the number in the file is larger than that,
either 1) the file's been damaged or 2) the file was produced after the
number was raised in the kernel.

In case 1), the number can't be trusted, so don't rely on it to attempt
to fix the original length field in the pcap or pcapng header.

In case 2), the system was probably running a version of libpcap that
didn't miscalculate the original length, so it probably doesn't need to
be fixed.

This avoids the possibility of the product of the number of descriptors
and the size of descriptors won't overflow an unsigned 32-bit integer.
